<title>LUXEMBOURG: EU ministers agree 'spy-in-the-cab' rules.</title>
<headline>EU ministers agree 'spy-in-the-cab' rules.</headline>
<dateline>LUXEMBOURG 1997-06-17</dateline>
<text>
<p>European Union transport ministers agreed on Tuesday to force new lorries and coaches registered from July 2000 to carry digital &quot;spies-in-the-cab&quot; to monitor drivers' speed and time spent behind the wheel.</p>
<p>But ministers dropped plans to retrofit the new device in existing vehicles, meaning the new-style tachographs will not penetrate the EU vehicle fleet completely until the end of the next decade.</p>
<p>Ahead of Tuesday's meeting, Belgium, Greece, Spain, Ireland, Italy, Portugal and Sweden had blocked the retrofit option, mainly on cost grounds.</p>
<p>But old vehicles needing replacement tachographs from July 2000 will have to fit digital devices rather than the old waxed-disc design.</p>
<p>The proposal sets rules for the construction, installation, use and checking of electronic tachographs, intended to replace an existing system seen as easy to fiddle.</p>
</text>
